MURINE TYPHUS - USA: (CALIFORNIA)
*********************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 6 Aug 2021
Source: Live Science [edited]
https://www.livescience.com/woman-gets-typhus-california-rat.html


A California woman who thought she had COVID-19 turned out to have typhus. The woman of Monrovia, California, said that when she started to experience symptoms of fatigue, fever and headache, she suspected she had COVID-19, according to local news outlet KTLA. But a COVID-19 test came back negative.

However, [the patient] continued to feel sick for weeks. She finally went back to her doctor, who asked if she had recently had any contact with wild animals. She remembered she had disposed of a dead rat in her backyard, KTLA reported. That information eventually led doctors to diagnose her with typhus, a bacterial disease spread by fleas and lice.

One form of typhus, called epidemic typhus, is caused by the bacteria _Rickettsia prowazekii_ and spread by lice, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). The disease caused millions of deaths in previous centuries, but it is now rare worldwide; cases are occasionally seen in areas with poor hygiene and extreme overcrowding, CDC says.

But the commonest form of typhus in the US is called murine typhus, which is caused by the bacteria _Rickettsia typhi_ and spread by fleas, according to CDC. Although relatively rare in the US, the disease still pops up in tropical and subtropical climates, including areas of Southern California, Texas, and Hawaii. Indeed, in 2018, an outbreak of fleaborne typhus infected dozens in the Los Angeles area, Live Science previously reported.

[The patient]'s doctors said she likely contracted typhus from infected fleas carried by the rat. When [the patient] posted her story to the social media site Nextdoor, she discovered that another person in her neighborhood had also recently been diagnosed with typhus after disposing of a dead rat, KTLA reported.

Symptoms of murine typhus typically start within 2 weeks of infection, and include fever, chills, body aches, nausea, vomiting and rash. The disease is treatable with the antibiotic doxycycline, according to CDC. Most people completely recover, sometimes even without treatment. People can reduce their risk of murine typhus by avoiding exposure to fleas, for instance by using flea medication for pets and keeping rodents away from their homes.

After her experience, [the patient] advises people not to take a do-it-yourself approach to disposing of dead animals. "If you see something in your yard, call someone who can dispose of it safely and don't try to do it yourself," she told KTLA.

[byline: Rachael Rettner]

